# W1': a `|>` chain directly after a value-position css"…" literal (the
# DQUOTE escape-hatch delimiter — this case deliberately pins the dquote+css
# corner of the lang x delimiter matrix; the parser unit matrix covers all
# six) NESTED inside a larger Go expression in a `{ }` interpolation
# (`wrap(css"…" |> minify)`). Contrast a pipe at the INTERP'S OWN top-level
# seed (`{ css"…" |> minify }`), which parsePipe already strips into a normal
# pipe Stage and is unaffected — this only fires once the literal is buried
# inside a call argument, past parsePipe's own top-level split. Caught at
# parse time (parseInterp's pre-check over the seed, run before analyze.go's
# deferred SplitGoExprElements split even exists), so the diagnostic wins
# over the later, generic skeleton parse failure the same broken text would
# otherwise hit. No filter package or `wrap` definition is needed: the
# rejection is purely syntactic, before any name resolves.
-- input.gsx --
package demo

component Page() {
	<div>{ wrap(css"c{x:1}" |> minify) }</div>
}
-- invoke --
Page()
-- diagnostics.golden --
4:26: whole-literal pipelines are not supported in Go-expression position; wrap the literal in a function call instead
-- render.golden --
